General interval comment: Gradiational color contact with underlying layer from 13-25 cm. Appears red by comparison with underlying interval.
Appears slightly greenish by comparision with the overlying layer.
Appears slightly greyer than the overlying section.

The dominant color is a reddish grey-brown (7.5YR 5/3) with decimeter scale banding towards redder (7YR 5/3), more clayey intervals. Relatively rich-foraminiferal blebs or layers occur interspersed with more clay rich, red patches.
Grey with occasional indistinct mottles and horizons, and slightly redder patches.
Grey with occasional indistinct mottles and horizons; texture suggests more foraminifera than in the preceding interval.
Grades from a greener to redder from top to bottom. Likely that the greener color corresponds to relatively diatom rich sediments as is found in other sections in Core 2H.
Appears more saturated than hues in the following section, with indistinct mottling from redder to greener cm-scale patches.
Indistinct mottles from darker to lighter grey. From 101-112cm dominant lithology is likely a nannofossil foraminiferal ooze.
Predominatly reddish brown (5YR 5/3) with decimeter scale variation with reddish grey-brown (7.5 YR 5/3). Distinct, foraminiferal rich-sediments fill the abundant Zoophycus-sized burrows.
The dominant color is a reddish grey-brown (7.5YR 5/3) with redder mottles  (7YR 5/3) and a general down-interval trend towards greyer sediments.
Grey with occasional redder mottles.

Gradiational contact between overlying grey strata and underlying, heavily saturated red-to-green greyish clays. Interval is distinquished by the abundance of foraminifera, which visually match those observed elsewhere in Core 2H known to be nannofossil foraminiferal oozes.

Dominant lithology is dark greenish gray nannofossil ooze with diatoms.  A secondary color of reddish brown (5YR 5/3) occurs from 102-116 cm, an interval which also contains burrows filled with greyish nannofossil foraminiferal ooze.
Grades from darker to lighter greenish grey, with occasional redder horizons.
Transitional interval between overlying and underlying strata; fariy sharp contact at 61cm.
Moderate to heavy bioturbation with diagenetic rings around some burrows.
A darker horizon from 104-112 cm.
Rather than a solid grayish brown this interval appears rather reddish brown with green to grey mottles and horizons.

The dominant color is a reddish grey-brown (7.5YR 5/3) with decimeter scale banding towards redder (7YR 5/3), more silty, oxide-rich intervals. Relatively rich-foraminiferal blebs or cm-decimeter scale layers occur interspersed with more oxide- rich, red patches.
Like overlying interval but with less foraminiferal-rich banding

Noteworthy that the green horizons lack notable elevation in diatoms (as with previous green decimeter scale horizons). Green interval also appears to be much less bioturbated, given that green horizons appear to be a primary feature.
Bottom of interval (40-51 cm) likely a nannofossil ooze with foraminifera.

Secondary color of 10YR 5/1 present in reddish horizons at 64-71, 71-85 (faint), 85-120 (reddish background), 119-125, and 131-137 cm. Red interval appear relatively silt and oxide rich. A cm-scale rock sits along core liner (archive half) at 54-57 cm and is unclear if it represents fall-in or an in situ rock. A band of muddy sands with foraminifera is present at 33-52 cm.
Secondary color of 10YR 5/1 present in reddish horizons at 38-59, 83-101, and 126-136 cm.
Normally graded muddy sands (lithogenic) with foraminifera with crude bedding. Greyer foraminiferal sands from 6-13 and 16-19cm and greener foramiferal silts with nannofossils from 2-6 and 13-15cm.
Sharp contact with overlying sands and underlying tanner sediments.
Secondary color of 10YR 5/1 present in reddish horizons at 0-24 and 54-58 cm.
Bedded sands with interbedded sandier, greener layers, and redder brown, less sandy layers.
Manganese nodule at 138-141 cm.
Mottling with lighter tan and redder tan.
Decimeter scale banding with redder or greyer intervals.

Clearly bioturbated horizon with overlying unit. Bioturbated contact spans from 110-119 cm.  Over the same interval small 'rocks' of likely diagenetic origin (diagenetically altered Mn-nodules)occur in clumps (possibly remains of burrows). At 82 and 88 cm small Manganese nodules are present.
Manganese nodules present from 40-125 cm, with a single large nodule at 74-80 cm. The Mn-nodule at 123-124cm has a diagenetic greenish color. Small black flecks occur throughout.
Small mm-scale manganese nodules and black sulfide flecks present throughout with increasing density down section (particularly 63-79 cm).
Abundant Mn-nodule fragments and black flecks.
Abundant, large Mn-nodules at 30-31, 37-45, 50-57, 58-63, 71-77, and 94-99 cm.
Few, rare Mn-nodule flecks (small nodule at 61-62 cm). Grey mottles throughout (faint) and rare redder mottles (faint) from 47-93 cm.
Few, rare Mn-nodule flecks. Grey mottles throughout (faint). Large Mn-nodule at 110-120 cm).
Few, rare Mn-nodule flecks. Grey mottles throughout (faint). Fracture from 45-61cm. Banded red, oxide beds from 101-113, 126 (faint), 138-150 cm (faint).
Large Mn-nodules at 70-77 and 26-29cm. Grey mottles throughout (faint). Banded faint red, oxide beds scattered throughout (2, 23,31-37, 58-69, and 95-107 cm).

Grey mottles throughout (faint). Banded faint red, oxide beds scattered throughout 9, 116-126, 60-66 cm. Offset in mottles and beds at 58-71 cm may reflect a fracture/fault or movement within the core liner.
Grey mottles throughout (faint).

Mottling and oxide banding gives Section 1 the appearance of being light to dark grey-purple (dominant color- 2.5Y 6/2) with varying amounts of overlying reddish banding.  Reddish oxide banding occurs on decimeter scales along the length of the core.
Mottling and oxide banding gives the top interval of Section2 the appearance of being light to dark grey-purple.

Distinguished from overlying sediments by distinct bioturbation mottling.  Interval is lighter at the top (15-33 cm) and darker grey at the bottom (33-58 cm).  A small Mn-nodule is present at 53-56 cm.
Moderate to heavy bioturbation with decimeter scale color variation between darker and lighter (5GY 8/1 to 5GY 7/1) light greenish grey.
Half-cm wide green glauconitic banding dispersed from 25-53 cm.
White interval mottled by grey to purplish grey mottles.
Two prominant green glauconitic bands at 98 and 103 cm.
White interval mottled by grey to purplish grey mottles.
Prominant green glauconitic layers at 13, 16, and 30-31cm, with rare white mottles near the contact with the overlying strata.
White interval mottled by grey to purplish grey mottles.
Prominant green glauconitic layer at 82 cm, with a small overlying Mn-nodule at 77 cm.
White interval mottled by grey to purplish grey mottles.
All light greenish grey intervals in Section 5 vary between 5GY 8/1 and N 7 (light grey).  This interval, like that from ~33-54cm is more grey than light greenish grey.
Faint green glauconitic horizon from 5-6 cm; bioturbation ranges from heavy (near top) to moderate (near bottom) of the interval
White interval mottled by grey mottles.
Prominant green glauconitic horizon at 54 cm.
Thoroughly bioturbated with overlying and underlying strata
Green glauconitic layers at 111, 114, and 119 cm and scattered layers from 125 to 138cm
Mottled by purplish grey mottles.
Brown and grey mottles, although the lower contact with underlying sediments remain sharp.

Decimeter scale variation in bioturbation (moderate to heavy) and color (towards greyer and/or whiter sediments).  Faint to prominent green glauconitic horizons at 29-32, 40, 92-100, and 122-125 cm.  A white concentration of diagenetic calcite occurs at 41-44 cm.
Very rare brown mottles.
Mottling includes rare brown, Zoophycus-sized burrows and smaller, Planolites burrows into over- and underlying light greenish grey sediments.

Green glauconitic horizons at 80 and 83cm. Bioturbation traces concetrated at contacts with surrounding strata, with Planolites burrows at the top and larger, Zoophycus sized brown burrows from 98-108 cm.
Abundant dark and light mottling.
Green glauconitic layer at 141 cm.
this interval characterized by a chaotic combination of patches, blebs, and beds at various angles of the greenish and white lithologies observed in other sections

Color is a bit lighter than denoted by the Munsel color. 5-cm wide bands of darker and lighter pink, brown, and grey (all faint) occur with a decimeter scale frequency. Rare partially lithified mm-wide white layers occur.
Color is a bit lighter than denoted by the Munsel color. 5-cm wide bands of darker and lighter pink, brown, and grey (all faint) occur with a decimeter scale frequency.
Color is true to Munsell color.  Decemeter color banding occurs from darker to lighter pink, and slightly browner pink, with very occasional mottling.
Gradual variation in background color (not as defined decimeter scale banding), with a distinct pink layer (not distinguished by Munsell) from 39-41 cm. Rare browner intervals occur.
Color grades from a pale version of pink (5YR 8/3) at 18-67  cm to greyish, brownish pink (10YR 8/2) from 67-110cm. Bioturbation clear in browner interval, likely due to diagenetic sulfides.
Mottled with darker brown (10YR 5/3).
On the pink (5YR 8/2) end of the scale.

Decimeter scale color variation from a browner (10YR 8/2) to a pinker (10YR 8/3, dominant color) pinkish brown.  Browner intervals clearly bioturbated, although relatively completely in comparison to surrounding sediments.

Color grades from greyish, brownish pink (10YR 8/2) to a pale version of pink (5YR 8/3). Clear bioturbation from top to bottom. Brown background color intensified in burrows, likely diagenetic sulfides.  Mottling and brown/grey essentially absent from the bottom 50 cm of the section.

Decimeter scale color variation from a browner (10YR 8/2) to a pinker (10YR 8/3, dominant color) pinkish brown.  Browner intervals clearly bioturbated and containing diagenetic sulfur. Color variation internally also includes relative abrupt contacts between color bands. Relatively lithified layer from 12-18.5, contains a very fine chert layer.
Distinctive 'blocky' colored chert with white (N 8), pale brown (10YR 7/4), and dark brown (10YR3/3) mottles and layers.
With darker mottles.

A greyer pinkish brown color (10YR 7/2) dominants in a fairly homogenized interval from 0-14cm. Clear bioturbation mottles (light pink, 5YR 8/3) on a brown background with diffuse sulfide mottles in Chondrites sized burrows.
Two decimeter scale intervals are browner (10YR 7/3). Clear bioturbation mottles (light pink, 5YR 8/3 and browner) on a brown background with diffuse sulfide mottles in Chondrites sized burrows.

Decimeter scale intervals are browner (10YR 7/3) to whiter (clear pink-white, off the lightness charts on Munsell). Clear bioturbation mottles (light pink, 5YR 8/3 and browner) with diffuse sulfide mottles in Chondrites sized burrows.

Decimeter scale variation from pinker light tan (10YR 8/3) to a greyer light tan (10YR 8/1) to a dark greyer light tan (10YR 6/2, only present from 82-88 cm). Bioturbation mottles clear throughout and color breaks between three dominant colors typically sharp.
Moderately to heavily bioturbated with rare much lighter burrows.  Mottling grades from relatively heavy to moderate through the interval.
Color banded interval of Section 2, with color bands on the scale of 5-cm and including the browner 10YR 8/3, the greyer 10YR 7/1), and the pinker (10YR 8/3).
Color generally homogenous with small burrows present in many intervals.
Bioturbation heavy to moderate.  A distinct darker pinky brown (approaching 10YR 7/3) interval with sharp upper and lower contacts occurs, diagonally, from 38-40 cm.
Mostly very dark brown chert with come lighter, tanner mottles.

Textured dark grey brown (10YR 4/1) with constiuent colors being both lighter (10YR 5/2) and darker (10YR 4/2) grey in addition to the dominant grey brown. Tan mottling occurs (10YR 8/4), with a particularly large bleb at 55-59 cm.
Large tan mottles (10YR 8/3) from 81-109 cm, with a highly mottled tan layer from 109-115 cm.
Smaller pinkish white mottles (5YR 8/3) in a slighly greyer brown interval.

Cm-scale diffuse whitish pink (5YR 8/3) diagenetic blebs. Sulfide flecks and diffuse mottling concentrated, typically around burrows. The boundary between nannofossil chalk and nannofossil chalk with radiolarians is unclear as it is not marked by any change in the visual appearance of the core.  Section 4, 45 cm is a nannofossil chalk and Section 5, 15 cm is a nannofossil chalk with radiolarians, with this interval bracketing the depth over which the lithological change must occur.
Cm-scale diffuse whitish pink (5YR 8/3) diagenetic blebs, with sulfide flecks and diffuse mottling.

Cm-scale diffuse whitish pink (5YR 8/3) diagenetic blebs, many with pink diagenetic rings. Cross-cutting pink/white bleb across the lighter/darker intervals in Section 5, speaks to the diagenetic origin of the whitish pink blebs. Discrete concentrates of sulfide flecks and small, approx. Chondrites sized brown mottling. Tiny light brown in-filled fractures at 25, 43-48, and (much longer) 56-74 cm.

Cm-scale diffuse whitish pink (5YR 8/3) diagenetic blebs, some with pink diagenetic rings. Sulfide flecks and diffuse mottling concentrated, typically around burrows. Two fractures from 84-91 and 94-98 cm.
Mm- to cm-scale diffuse whitish pink (5YR 8/3) diagenetic blebs.
Mm- to cm-scale diffuse whitish pink (5YR 8/3) diagenetic blebs.
Rare light tan to light pink (colors around 10YR 8/3) mottles, with sharp to diagenetic hazy boundaries.
Rare light tan to light pink (colors around 10YR 8/3) mottles, with sharp to diagenetic hazy boundaries.
Mottled pinkish (10YR 8/2) from 5-9 cm.

Rare light tan to light pink (colors around 10YR 8/3) mottles from Chondrites to Zoophycus size, with sharp to diagenetic hazy boundaries. Occasionally concentrated sulfidic flecks occur in rings around particularly distinct burrows.

Rare light tan to light pink (colors around 10YR 8/3) mottles from Chondrites to Zoophycus size, with sharp to diagenetic hazy boundaries. Occasionally concentrated sulfidic flecks occur in rings around particularly distinct burrows. Note, there is an unclear boundary between nannofossil chalk with radiolarians (lowermost sample Section 1, 62 cm) and nannofossil chalks (topmost sample Section 3, 74 cm). Section 2 is simply assigned as nannofossil chalk with radiolarians.

Rare light tan to light pink (colors around 10YR 8/3) mottles from Chondrites to Zoophycus size, with sharp to diagenetic hazy boundaries. Occasionally concentrated sulfidic flecks occur in rings around particularly distinct burrows (particularly from 39-52 cm).

Rare light tan to light pink (colors around 10YR 8/3) mottles from Chondrites to Zoophycus size, with sharp to diagenetic hazy boundaries. Occasionally concentrated sulfidic flecks occur in rings around particularly distinct burrows.

Rare light tan to light pink (colors around 10YR 8/3) mottles from Chondrites to Zoophycus size, with sharp to diagenetic hazy boundaries. Occasionally concentrated sulfidic flecks occur in rings around particularly distinct burrows.
Underlain by 2 cm of relatively lithofied sediments.

Rare light tan to light pink (colors around 10YR 8/3) mottles from Chondrites to Zoophycus size, with sharp to diagenetic hazy boundaries. Occasionally concentrated sulfidic flecks occur in rings around particularly distinct burrows.

Rare light tan to light pink (colors around 10YR 8/3) mottles of Zoophycus size with diagenetic hazy boundaries. Occasionally concentrated sulfidic flecks occur in rings around particularly distinct burrows (see 5-7 and 48-51 cm).
Rare light tan to light pink (colors around 10YR 8/3) mottles of Zoophycus size with diagenetic hazy boundaries.
Rare light tan to light pink (colors around 10YR 8/3) mottles of Chondrites to Zoophycus size with diagenetic hazy boundaries. A single burrow concentration of sulfide flecks at 9-11 cm.
Light gray with Planolites to (most) Zoophycus sized pink (5YR 8/3) mottles with sharp to hazy borders and layers. Section 1 is over all far greyer than the sections that follow.
Rare pink (5YR 8/3) mottles.

Light gray with Planolites to Zoophycus sized pink (5YR 8/3) mottles with sharp to hazy borders and layers. Distinctly more mottled than the upper portion of Section 2. Sulfide flecks occur in concentrations have the greatest densities at 82-96 cm in association with burrows
Light gray with Planolites to Zoophycus sized pink (5YR 8/3) mottles with sharp to hazy borders and layers. Sulfide flecks occur in concentrations have the greatest densities at 9-16 and 70-74 cm.
Light gray with Planolites to Zoophycus sized pink (5YR 8/3) mottles with sharp to hazy borders and layers.

Light gray with Planolites to Zoophycus sized pink (5YR 8/3) mottles with sharp to hazy borders and layers.  Discrete pink layers occur at 4-7 and 35-37 cm.  The dominate light grey color darkens down section.  Sulfide flecks occur in concentrations, often around burrows, with the greatest concentration in Section 4 at 93-105 cm.

Bubble gum pink splotches from 0-2 and 13-15 cm and heavy pink-black (5YR 3/4) ?sulfide flecks from 8-12 cm overlie the dominant Munsell color (5YR 8/3) of the majority of the sediment in this interval.
Munsell color fails to capture the pink undertone of the chert.

Pink to pale pink (Munsell color selected is too dark, but closest match) variation in color on decimeter scales.  Four stacked pink beds from 30-39 cm. Bioturbation appears moderate in comparison to following sections but could be due to the intensity of pink coloration (mottles more readily apparent).

Pale pink (Munsell color selected is too dark, but closest match), heavily bioturbated with slight background variation in the saturation of pink and intensity of bioturbation (moderately heavy to heavy).
Pale pink (Munsell color selected is too dark, but closest match), nearly completely bioturbated.
Darker color (10YR 6/3 to 10YR 6/2) from 0-33 cm appears to arise from the greater density of ?sulfides in burrows, especially from 18-33 cm. Occasional, small pink (5YR 8/3 but paler) mottles.

Large decimeter scale pink blebs (5YR 8/3 but paler), occasionally with darker pink rings and a bubble-gum pink spot at 93 cm. Pink spots appear diagenetic given their cross cutting relationship with  underlying Planolites burrows,
Pink sediments between 5YR 8/3 and 7.5YR 8/3.
Pink sediments between 5YR 8/3 and 7.5YR 8/3. A single bubble-gum pink spot occurs at 145 cm.
Pink sediments between 5YR 8/3 and 7.5YR 8/3.
Pink sediments between 5YR 8/3 and 7.5YR 8/3.
Munsell color fails to capture the pink undertone of the chert.
Pink sediments between 5YR 8/3 and 7.5YR 8/3.
Abundant lighter grey Planolites mottles, particularly from 65-70 cm.
Cm-scale color variation between the bluer (10Y 8/1) and greyer (5Y 8/1) grey.
Cm-scale color variation between the bluer (10Y 8/1) and pinker (10Y 7/2) grey.
Porcellinite fragments from 0-5 cm and a relatively well-lithified biscuit from 16-21 cm.
Section 1 is comprised of alternating chalks and relatively harder sediments from porcellinite to cherts.  The porcellinite/chert occur at 5-11, 22-25, 32-35, 50-59, 59-63, and 65-68 cm.
The CC is comprised of chalks and capped by relatively harder sediments from porcellinite to cherts.  The porcellinite/cherts occur at 0-10 and 45-49 cm.
